04241nam a22005535i 9780300163469DE-B159720230529094047.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||230529t20191996ctu    fo  d z      eng d  a97803001634697 a10.12987/97803001634692doi  a(DE-B1597)485841  a(OCoLC)795711414  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  actucUS-CT 4aP99.5.J67 1996 7aLIT0000002bisacsh04a3021 aJosipovici, Gabriel, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aTouch /cGabriel Josipovici. 1aNew Haven, CT : bYale University Press, c[2019] 4cÂ©1996  a1 online resource (156 p.) :b16 b-w illus.  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tAcknowledgments -- tPrologue -- t1. The Lessons of the Hand -- t2. The Lime-Tree Bower and the Virgin of Amiens -- t3. Boundaries -- t4. Holding and Grasping -- t5. The Room -- t6. Addiction -- t7. Transgression -- t8. The Lesson of the Hand (2) -- t9. Praesentia -- t10. The King's Touch -- t11. The Therapy of Distance -- t12. The Therapy of Distance (2) -- t13. Relics -- t14. The Girdle and the River -- t15. 'A Goose which Has Grown in Scotland on a Tree' -- t16. Possessing Power -- t17. The Jewish Bride -- t18. First Steps -- t19. Kinetic Melodies -- t20. Kinetic Melodies (2) -- t21. Walker and World -- t22. Boundaries (2) -- t23. The Room (2) -- tAppendix -- tNotes -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aIn this brilliant new book, a preeminent literary thinker muses over the central question of how we can feel at home in the world, given that the world is independent of and indifferent to our wishes. Drawing on books and films, cultural history and his own experiences, Gabriel Josipovici argues that it is possible to feel comfortable in the world and in our relationships with others only if we value touch over sight, if we respect distance but also work to overcome it.Josipovici moves from a Charlie Chaplin movie to passages from Proust, from the world of sport to the world of addiction, from medieval pilgrimages to the cult of relics, from a wedding photograph of his grandparents to some of Chardin's most enigmatic paintings. Through these seemingly disparate topics he provides engaging and wise commentary on connection and communication in life. Contrasting the senses of sight and touch, Josipovici notes that although sight seems to give us the totality of what we behold, it is only when we walk or feel our way across the distances that things become more than images and begin to constitute the world in which we as touchers and not mere observers are included. If we depend on sight-which seems to offer a frictionless domination over reality-we may avoid the pains and uncertainties of living, but we also lose our involvement with life.Lucid, imaginative, and daring, Josipovici's book will inspire and, yes, deeply touch us all.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Mai 2023) 0aNonverbal communication. 0aTouch. 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / General.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertYale University Press eBook-Package Archive Pre-2000z97831105380140 cprintz978030006690640uhttps://doi.org/10.12987/978030016346940uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780300163469423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780300163469/original  a978-3-11-053801-4  Yale University Press eBook-Package Archive Pre-2000b2000  aEBA_FAO  aEBA_UCA_YUP  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aZDB-23-UCY